{
  "result": "An old river winds through my imagination, carrying driftwood memories and pebbled possibilities. I picture dawnlight gathering on the surface, a soft sheen like brushed silver, while fog curls upward, revealing fragments of voices from people I once overheard in trains, caf\u00e9s, playgrounds. Each voice becomes a small boat that slides into the water, testing balance, discovering currents. Some boats bear questions about purpose, others carry laughter stitched with unspoken fear, and a few bring nothing but comfortable silence. I like to believe the river listens patiently, absorbing every tone without judgment. It reminds me that water is both archive and revision, storing sediment while reshaping its bed. My own thoughts often feel like erratic minnows; they dart, collide, vanish beneath silt, reappear downstream. When I sit beside the metaphorical bank, thankful for stillness, the world insists on offering new interruptions: a humming alert, a stray advertisement, the clatter of neighbors rearranging furniture after midnight. Yet these interruptions eventually fall into rhythm with the current, transforming annoyance into curious syncopation. Perhaps this is why I continue daydreaming about expansive waterways instead of tidy spreadsheets: rivers refuse to stay frozen inside columns. They bend, swell, evaporate, and return as rain, proof that wandering can be a productive loop. The river teaches a quiet activism, a slow persistence that undercuts stone by patience rather than force. If I could speak its language fluently, I would ask how best to keep flowing without washing away the delicate bridges that allow us to meet.",
